Module kivakit.interfaces
Package com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.numeric

Interface Quantizable

All Superinterfaces:
DoubleQuantizable, Stringable, StringSource
All Known Subinterfaces:
Countable, Identifiable, Indexable<Element>, Indexed, IntegerNumeric<Value>, LengthOfTime<Duration>, LongKeyed, PointInTime<Time,Duration>, QuantumComparable<Value>, Sized, TimeMeasurement
All Known Implementing Classes:
ArgumentList, BaseCount, BaseIndexedMap, BaseList, BaseResourceList, BaseSet, BaseTime, BitCount, Bytes, ConcurrentMutableCount, Count, Day, DayOfWeek, Differences, Duration, Estimate, FileList, FilePath, Hour, HourOfWeek, Identifier, IndexedNameMap, IntegerIdentifier, LinkedObjectList, LocalTime, Maximum, MessageList, Minimum, Minute, MutableCount, NetworkPath, ObjectList, ObjectSet, PackagePath, PackageReference, Path, Range, Rate, ResourceList, ResourcePath, Second, Stack, StackTrace, StringList, StringPath, Time, ValidationIssues, Week, Year
Functional Interface:
This is a functional interface and can therefore be used as the assignment target for a lambda expression or method reference.
@FunctionalInterface public interface Quantizable extends DoubleQuantizable, Stringable
A quantizable object can be turned into a quantum. A quantum is a discrete value and is represented by the Java primitive type "long". Quanta are a unification point among classes which have a quantum representation, allowing certain operations to be applied to quantizable objects uniformly (such as converting to and from string representations or using the quantum value as an index or identifier in a map or data store).

Examples of quantizable objects include objects that are Indexed, Identifiable or LongKeyed. In addition, objects like Time, Duration, and Count are quantizable. In the cases of time and duration objects, the quantum is the number of milliseconds. Quantizable values can also be compared and checked for zero or non-zero.

Quantizable provides a converter which can convert between a String value and any Quantizable value. The value is instantiated by passing the quantum to a MapFactory.

Clients may extend QuantizableConverter (see kivakit-core) to quickly create a converter for any Quantizable value. For example, EdgeIdentifier provides a converter between String values and EdgeIdentifiers like this: 

 public static class Converter extends Quantizable.Converter<EdgeIdentifier>
 {
     public Converter( Listener<Message> listener)
     {
         super(listener, EdgeIdentifier::new);
     }
 }
